Observations from the Charts¶

Chart 1: Number of Patients by Age Group¶

  1. Highest Patient Volume in Older Age Groups:
    • The 61-70 age group has the highest number of patients (778), followed by 71-80 (643) and 81+ (553).
    • Older patients dominate the patient population, likely driven by procedures related to chronic conditions or age-related surgeries.
  2. Decline in Younger Age Groups:
    • The number of patients decreases significantly in younger age groups, with the lowest numbers observed in the 41-50 (388) and 31-40 (412) age groups.

Chart 2: Percentage of Claims by Patient Age Group¶

  1. 61-70 Age Group Drives the Majority of Claims:
    • This age group contributes 21.4% of claims, highlighting their importance as the primary target demographic.
  2. Significant Contribution by 71-80 and 81+ Age Groups:
    • Combined, these age groups contribute 33.5% of claims, making older patients the most important segment.
  3. Lower Contribution by Younger Groups:
    • The 18-30, 31-40, and 41-50 age groups collectively account for less than 35% of claims, showing less reliance on injectable anesthesia in these populations.

Recommendations¶

1. Focus on Older Patient Demographics¶

  • Key Driver:
    • Older patients (61+ years) dominate both patient volume and claims, making them the critical demographic for Product 2.
  • Actions:
    • Emphasize Safety and Efficacy:
      • Market Product 2 as a safer and more reliable option for older patients undergoing surgeries, particularly those related to cardiovascular, orthopedic, and general health procedures.
    • Collaborate with Geriatric HCPs:
      • Partner with specialists treating older populations, such as cardiologists, orthopedic surgeons, and general practitioners, to promote Product 2.
    • Address Recovery Times:
      • Highlight faster recovery times and lower side effects for older patients to differentiate Product 2 from competitors like Product 3.

2. Target High-Claim Age Groups with Tailored Campaigns¶

  • 61-70 Age Group:
    • Focus the majority of marketing efforts on the 61-70 age group, as they contribute the highest claims volume.
    • Develop targeted messaging that showcases Product 2s suitability for procedures common in this age group, such as joint replacements, cardiac surgeries, and diagnostic interventions.
  • 71-80 and 81+ Age Groups:
    • Emphasize the benefits of Product 2 for frail or high-risk patients, leveraging its safety and efficacy for complex procedures.

3. Engage HCPs Who Serve Older Patients¶

  • Key Driver:
    • HCPs specializing in older patient care are critical to driving claims for Product 2.
  • Actions:
    • Education and Training:
      • Conduct workshops and seminars for anesthesiologists, cardiologists, and orthopedic surgeons on Product 2s advantages in treating older patients.
    • Incentive Programs:
      • Offer rebates or loyalty rewards to HCPs who consistently prescribe Product 2 for older patients.
    • Collaborate with Long-Term Care Facilities:
      • Partner with nursing homes and geriatric care centers to integrate Product 2 into their anesthesia protocols.

4. Expand Market Share in Younger Demographics¶

  • Key Driver:
    • Although younger groups contribute less to claims, they represent an untapped market for growth.
  • Actions:
    • Promote Versatility:
      • Highlight Product 2s applicability for procedures common among younger populations, such as sports injury surgeries (orthopedic) and diagnostic interventions.
    • Leverage Preventive Procedures:
      • Target patients undergoing preventive surgeries or exploratory procedures, emphasizing Product 2s cost-effectiveness.

5. Counter Competitor (Product 3) Growth¶

  • Key Driver:
    • Product 3 likely captures older patients by marketing its efficacy and safety for complex procedures.
  • Actions:
    • Head-to-Head Marketing:
      • Launch campaigns comparing Product 2 to Product 3, focusing on superior recovery times, lower side effects, and cost savings.
    • Differentiate on Price:
      • Offer competitive pricing or bundled deals for procedures targeting older demographics to win back market share.

Expected Outcomes¶

  1. Increase Claims Volume for Older Patients:
    • By focusing on the 61+ age groups, Product 2 can capture a larger share of high-volume procedures.
  2. Expand into Younger Age Groups:
    • Targeted campaigns will open opportunities in underrepresented demographics, increasing overall market share.
  3. Counteract Competitor Dominance:
    • Differentiating Product 2 based on price and efficacy will mitigate Product 3s growth.

Observations from the Charts¶

Chart 1: New Writers by Procedure Code and Year¶

  1. 2016 Dominance of Product 1 (J1885 - Leader):

    • Product 1 had the highest number of new writers in 2016 (492), significantly outperforming all other products.
    • Product 2 (J2250 - Variant) had 285 new writers, second only to Product 1 but still lagging behind Product 3 (J3010 - Main Competitor), which had 344 new writers.

  2. 2017 Decline for Product 2:

    • The number of new writers for Product 2 dropped significantly from 285 in 2016 to 111 in 2017, indicating poor adoption efforts.
    • Product 3 (119 new writers) maintained a competitive edge, while Product 4 (J2704 - Alternative Competitor) saw an increase (152 new writers).

  3. 2018 Almost No New Writers for Product 2:

    • Product 2 gained only 34 new writers in 2018, a sharp decline compared to competitors.
    • Product 4 attracted the highest number of new writers in 2018 (140), demonstrating growing traction in the market.

Chart 2: Continuing Writers by Year and Brand¶

  1. Stable Continuation for Product 1 (J1885):

    • Product 1 retained the highest number of continuing writers (488 in 2017 to 496 in 2018), indicating strong loyalty and consistent market presence.

  2. Product 3 (J3010) Growth in Retention:

    • Product 3 saw a significant increase in continuing writers, from 297 in 2017 to 436 in 2018, showcasing strong retention and growing loyalty among HCPs.

  3. Product 2 (J2250) Struggles to Retain Writers:

    • While the number of continuing writers for Product 2 increased slightly from 165 in 2017 to 192 in 2018, this growth is minimal compared to competitors.
    • Retention efforts are falling short, leading to stagnation in market share growth.

  4. Product 4 (J2704) Steady Growth:

    • The alternative competitor steadily grew its number of continuing writers from 35 in 2017 to 128 in 2018, showing increased HCP adoption.

Recommendations¶

1. Re-Engage Lapsed Writers¶

  • Target New Writers Lost Since 2016:
    • Identify and re-engage HCPs who wrote prescriptions for Product 2 in 2016 but did not continue in subsequent years.
    • Use surveys or direct outreach to understand the reasons for attrition and offer tailored incentives to bring them back.
  • Rebuild Momentum Among New Writers:
    • Implement an aggressive campaign to onboard new writers through free trials, rebates, and education programs tailored to their specialties (e.g., anesthesiology, cardiology).

2. Focus on Retaining Existing Writers¶

  • Retention Programs:
    • Launch a loyalty program for existing writers, rewarding consistent use of Product 2 over time.
    • Provide exclusive discounts or bonuses to high-volume prescribers.
  • Educational Support:
    • Offer updated training and resources highlighting Product 2s efficacy and safety compared to competitors, especially targeting procedures relevant to the writers specialties.

3. Counter Product 3’s Growth¶

  • Competitive Differentiation:
    • Highlight Product 2s advantages over Product 3, such as cost-effectiveness, fewer side effects, or faster onset.
    • Disseminate real-world evidence or testimonials from satisfied HCPs to build trust and credibility.
  • Aggressive Pricing in Key Regions:
    • Implement dynamic pricing strategies in territories where Product 3 is growing rapidly to make Product 2 more attractive.

4. Leverage Product 4’s Momentum¶

  • Collaborate in Niche Segments:
    • Since Product 4 is growing in niche markets, identify shared specialties where Product 2 could outperform and target those with focused campaigns.
  • Head-to-Head Campaigns:
    • Use comparative studies to showcase Product 2s superiority over Product 4 in safety, efficacy, or cost-effectiveness.

5. Expand the New Writer Base¶

  • Incentive-Based Outreach:
    • Provide significant financial incentives for new writers to prescribe Product 2, especially in underpenetrated specialties like gastroenterology and neurology.
  • Data-Driven Targeting:
    • Use analytics to identify HCPs likely to adopt injectable anesthesia and target them with personalized campaigns.
  • Hospital Partnerships:
    • Collaborate with hospitals to make Product 2 the default choice for new procedures, onboarding new HCPs as prescribers.

6. Strengthen Relationships with Anesthesiologists¶

  • Key Driver:
    • Anesthesiologists are critical for maintaining and growing Product 2s market share.
  • Actions:
    • Partner with anesthesiology associations to develop training programs and sponsor conferences.
    • Offer bundled discounts on Product 2 for high-use hospitals and surgical centers.

Expected Outcomes¶

  1. Rebuild Market Share:
    • Re-engaging lapsed and new writers will help recover market share lost to competitors.
  2. Increase Retention:
    • Loyalty programs and educational initiatives will ensure continued use among current writers.
  3. Counter Competitive Growth:
    • Aggressive differentiation and pricing will slow down the growth of Product 3 and Product 4.
  4. Expand New Markets:
    • Focused efforts on new HCPs and niche segments will create additional opportunities for Product 2.
